\section{Discussion}

\subsection*{Limitations}
The SIR model assumes a closed population with homogeneous mixing and constant parameters, which are not fully realistic for COVID-19.  In particular, transmission rates change over time due to policy interventions and behavioral responses, such as lockdowns and mask mandates. 

Additionally, the dataset does not directly measure the number of infectious individuals, requiring the use of a rolling sum approximation.  This introduces error into the comparison between the model and observed data.

Finally, the model captures only a single wave of infections and cannot account for multiple waves or reinfections.

\subsection*{Future Work}
Future work could extend this model by incorporating time-varying parameters or using more complex models such as SEIR.  Additionally, improving estimates of the infectious population or incorporating additional data sources could lead to more accurate model fits.




